We use the Euclidean Algorithm to find $\gcd(b^2 + 11b + 30, b + 6)$.
\begin{align*}
\text{First, compute } &b^2 + 11b + 30 \text{ modulo } b+6: \\
&b^2 + 11b + 30 = (b^2 + 6b) + 5b + 30\\
&\quad= b(b + 6) + 5b + 30.
\end{align*}
Here, we simplify $b(b+6)$ modulo $(b+6)$ as this part gives remainder $0$. Thus, we are left with the remains:
\begin{align*}
5b + 30 \mod (b + 6).
\end{align*}
To simplify $5b + 30$ modulo $b + 6$, assume $b=6k$ (as $b$ is a multiple of $6$):
\begin{align*}
5(6k) + 30 &\equiv 30k + 30 \pmod{6k + 6}\\
&\equiv 30(k + 1) \pmod{6(k + 1)}.
\end{align*}
By factoring out 6, we have:
\begin{align*}
30(k + 1) &\equiv 5\cdot 6(k + 1) \equiv 0 \pmod{6(k + 1)}.
\end{align*}
Finally, the gcd we are looking for equals $\gcd(0, b + 6) = b + 6$, but since $b$ is a multiple of $1428$, which is itself a multiple of $6$, the constant terms add to this modulus.

Thus the greatest common divisor simplifies down to $\boxed{6}$.

