Question 182, Solution: Using nine points to represent 9 people, we are required to find the number of ways to connect these 9 points into several non-intersecting circles. It is easy to know that, to connect $\mathrm{n}$ points into a circle, there are exactly $\frac{(\mathrm{n}-1)!}{2}$ ways. Below, we divide into four cases:
(1) If there is only one circle of length 9, then there are exactly $\frac{8!}{2}=20160$ ways to connect;
(2) If connected into two circles, one of length 3 and one of length 6, then there are $\mathrm{C}_{9}^{3} \cdot \frac{21}{2} \cdot \frac{5!}{2}=5040$ ways to connect;
(3) If connected into two circles, one of length 4 and one of length 5, then there are $\mathrm{C}_{9}^{4} \cdot \frac{3!}{2} \cdot \frac{4!}{2}=4536$ ways to connect;
(4) If connected into three circles, then all lengths are 3, and there are $\frac{9!}{3!3!\cdot 3!} \cdot \frac{2!}{2} \cdot \frac{2!}{2} \cdot \frac{2!}{2}=280$ ways.
In summary, we know $N=20160+5040+4536+280=30016$. Therefore, the remainder when $N$ is divided by 1000 is 16.

