282. a) Prove that for any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n} ; b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$, the following inequality always holds:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sqrt{a_{1}^{2}+b_{1}^{2}} & +\sqrt{a_{2}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}}+\ldots+\sqrt{a_{n}^{2}+b_{n}^{2}} \geqslant \\
& \geqslant \sqrt{\left(a_{1}+a_{2}+\ldots+a_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(b_{1}+b_{2}+\ldots+b_{n}\right)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Under what conditions does equality hold?
b) A pyramid is called a right pyramid if a circle can be inscribed in its base and the center of this circle coincides with the base of the pyramid's height. Prove that a right pyramid has a smaller lateral surface area than any other pyramid of the same height, whose base has the same area and the same perimeter.

Note. The inequality in part a) is a special case of the so-called Minkowski inequality, which states that

$$
\begin{array}{r}
\sqrt{a_{1}^{2}+b_{1}^{2}+\ldots+l_{1}^{2}}+\sqrt{a_{2}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+l_{2}^{2}}+\ldots \\
\ldots+\sqrt{a_{n}^{2}+b_{n}^{2}+\ldots+l_{n}^{2}} \geqslant \\
>\sqrt{\left(a_{1}+\ldots+a_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(b_{1}+\ldots+b_{n}\right)^{2}+\ldots+\left(l_{1}+\ldots+l_{n}\right)^{2}}
\end{array}
$$

output:
282. a) First of all, we can consider all \(a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}; b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}\) to be positive from the very beginning; otherwise, we would change the signs of the negative numbers to the opposite: the left side of the inequality would not change, while the right side could only increase. Now consider the broken line \(A_{0} A_{1} A_{2} \ldots A_{n}\), such that the projections of segments \(A_{0} A_{1}, A_{1} A_{2}, \ldots, A_{n-1} A_{n}\) on the \(O x\) axis are equal to \(a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}\), and the projections of these segments on the \(O y\) axis are \(b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}\); let each vertex of the broken line be located to the right and above the preceding one (Fig. 32). In this case, from the Pythagorean theorem, it follows that

\[
\begin{gathered}
A_{0} A_{1}=\sqrt{a_{1}^{2}+b_{1}^{2}}, \quad A_{1} A_{2}=\sqrt{a_{2}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}}, \ldots, A_{n-1} A_{n}=\sqrt{a_{n}^{2}+b_{n}^{2}} \\
A_{0} A_{n}=\sqrt{\left(a_{1}+a_{2}+\ldots+a_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(b_{1}+b_{2}+\ldots+b_{n}\right)^{2}}
\end{gathered}
\]

from which the inequality of the problem follows.

The broken line \(A_{0} A_{1} A_{2} \ldots A_{n}\) will be equal to the segment \(A_{0} A_{n}\) only if all segments of this broken line are continuations of each other (the broken line is a straight line segment). It is easy to see that this condition will be met if \(\frac{a_{1}}{b_{1}}=\frac{a_{2}}{b_{2}}=\ldots=\frac{a_{n}}{b_{n}}\); only in this case does the equality hold

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \sqrt{a_{1}^{2}+b_{1}^{2}}+\sqrt{a_{2}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}}+\ldots+\sqrt{a_{n}^{2}+b_{n}^{2}}= \\
& \quad=\sqrt{\left(a_{1}+a_{2}+\ldots+a_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(b_{1}+b_{2}+\ldots+b_{n}\right)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

b). Let \(h\) be the height of the pyramid, \(a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}\) be the sides of the base \((a_{1}+a_{2}+\ldots+a_{n}=P)\), and \(b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}\) be the lengths of the perpendiculars dropped from the base of the height to the sides of the base \(\left(\frac{1}{2} a_{1} b_{1}+\frac{1}{2} a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+\frac{1}{2} a_{n} b_{n}=S\right)\). In this case, the lateral surface \(\Sigma\) of the pyramid will be equal to

\[
\frac{1}{2} a_{1} \sqrt{b_{1}^{2}+h^{2}}+\frac{1}{2} a_{2} \sqrt{b_{2}^{2}+h^{2}}+\ldots+\frac{1}{2} a_{n} \sqrt{b_{n}^{2}+h^{2}}
\]

But according to the inequality of part a)

\[
\begin{aligned}
& 2 \Sigma=\sqrt{\left(a_{1} b_{1}\right)^{2}+\left(a_{1} h\right)^{2}}+\sqrt{\left(a_{2} b_{2}\right)^{2}+\left(a_{2} h\right)^{2}}+\cdots \\
& \ldots+\sqrt{\left(a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(a_{n} h\right)^{2}} \geqslant \\
& \geqslant \sqrt{\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(a_{1} h+a_{2} h+\ldots+a_{n} h\right)^{2}}= \\
& \quad=\sqrt{4 S^{2}+h^{2} P^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

equality is achieved only if \(a_{1} b_{1}: a_{2} b_{2}: \ldots: a_{n} b_{n} = a_{1} h: a_{2} h: \ldots: a_{n} h\), i.e., \(b_{1}=b_{2}=\ldots=b_{n}\).

From this, the statement of the problem follows.

