Solution. Let's compare the squares of the given non-negative expressions:

$$
\begin{gathered}
(a+c)(b+d) \vee(\sqrt{a b}+\sqrt{c d})^{2} \\
a b+a d+c b+c d \vee a b+c d+2 \sqrt{a b c d}
\end{gathered}
$$

Subtract the sum $a b+c d$ from both sides of the inequality:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& b c+a d \vee 2 \sqrt{a b c d} \\
& b c+a d-2 \sqrt{a b c d} \vee 0
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $b c+a d-2 \sqrt{a b c d}=(\sqrt{b c}-\sqrt{a d})^{2} \geqslant 0$, then $(a+c)(b+d)>$ $(\sqrt{a b}+\sqrt{c d})^{2}$. Taking the square root of both sides of the inequality, we get $\sqrt{(a+c)(b+d)} \geqslant \sqrt{a b}+\sqrt{c d}$, which is what we needed to prove.

Remark. The inequality $b c+a d \geqslant$ $\geqslant 2 \sqrt{a b c d}$ can also be proven based on the relationship between the arithmetic mean and the geometric mean: the arithmetic mean of two non-negative numbers $b c$ and $a d$ is not less than their geometric mean, i.e.,

$$
\frac{b c+a d}{2} \geqslant \sqrt{a b c d}
$$

